Note:
Runa Standard Library: Weight Initialization Strategies

Various weight initialization methods for neural networks including
Xavier, He, random, and other initialization strategies.
:End Note

Import "../../math/core" as Math
Import "../../algorithms" as Algorithms
Import "../../../../collections" as Collections

Note: Xavier/Glorot Initialization
Process called "xavier_uniform" that takes shape as List[Integer] returns Algorithms.Matrix:
    Let fan_in be Float.from with value as shape[0]
    Let fan_out be Float.from with value as shape[1]
    Let limit be Math.sqrt with x as 6.0 divided by (fan_in + fan_out)
    
    Let data be list
    For i from 0 to shape[0] - 1:
        Let row be list
        For j from 0 to shape[1] - 1:
            Let value be random_uniform with min_val as negative limit and max_val as limit
            Add value to row
        Add row to data
    
    Return Algorithms.Matrix with:
        rows as shape[0]
        cols as shape[1]
        data as data

Process called "xavier_normal" that takes shape as List[Integer] returns Algorithms.Matrix:
    Let fan_in be Float.from with value as shape[0]
    Let fan_out be Float.from with value as shape[1]
    Let std be Math.sqrt with x as 2.0 divided by (fan_in + fan_out)
    
    Let data be list
    For i from 0 to shape[0] - 1:
        Let row be list
        For j from 0 to shape[1] - 1:
            Let value be random_normal with mean as 0.0 and std as std
            Add value to row
        Add row to data
    
    Return Algorithms.Matrix with:
        rows as shape[0]
        cols as shape[1]
        data as data

Note: He Initialization (for ReLU)
Process called "he_uniform" that takes shape as List[Integer] returns Algorithms.Matrix:
    Let fan_in be Float.from with value as shape[0]
    Let limit be Math.sqrt with x as 6.0 divided by fan_in
    
    Let data be list
    For i from 0 to shape[0] - 1:
        Let row be list
        For j from 0 to shape[1] - 1:
            Let value be random_uniform with min_val as negative limit and max_val as limit
            Add value to row
        Add row to data
    
    Return Algorithms.Matrix with:
        rows as shape[0]
        cols as shape[1]
        data as data

Process called "he_normal" that takes shape as List[Integer] returns Algorithms.Matrix:
    Let fan_in be Float.from with value as shape[0]
    Let std be Math.sqrt with x as 2.0 divided by fan_in
    
    Let data be list
    For i from 0 to shape[0] - 1:
        Let row be list
        For j from 0 to shape[1] - 1:
            Let value be random_normal with mean as 0.0 and std as std
            Add value to row
        Add row to data
    
    Return Algorithms.Matrix with:
        rows as shape[0]
        cols as shape[1]
        data as data

Note: LeCun Initialization
Process called "lecun_uniform" that takes shape as List[Integer] returns Algorithms.Matrix:
    Let fan_in be Float.from with value as shape[0]
    Let limit be Math.sqrt with x as 3.0 divided by fan_in
    
    Let data be list
    For i from 0 to shape[0] - 1:
        Let row be list
        For j from 0 to shape[1] - 1:
            Let value be random_uniform with min_val as negative limit and max_val as limit
            Add value to row
        Add row to data
    
    Return Algorithms.Matrix with:
        rows as shape[0]
        cols as shape[1]
        data as data

Process called "lecun_normal" that takes shape as List[Integer] returns Algorithms.Matrix:
    Let fan_in be Float.from with value as shape[0]
    Let std be Math.sqrt with x as 1.0 divided by fan_in
    
    Let data be list
    For i from 0 to shape[0] - 1:
        Let row be list
        For j from 0 to shape[1] - 1:
            Let value be random_normal with mean as 0.0 and std as std
            Add value to row
        Add row to data
    
    Return Algorithms.Matrix with:
        rows as shape[0]
        cols as shape[1]
        data as data

Note: Random Initialization
Process called "random_uniform_init" that takes shape as List[Integer] and min_val as Float and max_val as Float returns Algorithms.Matrix:
    Let data be list
    For i from 0 to shape[0] - 1:
        Let row be list
        For j from 0 to shape[1] - 1:
            Let value be random_uniform with min_val as min_val and max_val as max_val
            Add value to row
        Add row to data
    
    Return Algorithms.Matrix with:
        rows as shape[0]
        cols as shape[1]
        data as data

Process called "random_normal_init" that takes shape as List[Integer] and mean as Float and std as Float returns Algorithms.Matrix:
    Let data be list
    For i from 0 to shape[0] - 1:
        Let row be list
        For j from 0 to shape[1] - 1:
            Let value be random_normal with mean as mean and std as std
            Add value to row
        Add row to data
    
    Return Algorithms.Matrix with:
        rows as shape[0]
        cols as shape[1]
        data as data

Note: Zero and One Initialization
Process called "zeros_init" that takes shape as List[Integer] returns Algorithms.Matrix:
    Let data be list
    For i from 0 to shape[0] - 1:
        Let row be list
        For j from 0 to shape[1] - 1:
            Add 0.0 to row
        Add row to data
    
    Return Algorithms.Matrix with:
        rows as shape[0]
        cols as shape[1]
        data as data

Process called "ones_init" that takes shape as List[Integer] returns Algorithms.Matrix:
    Let data be list
    For i from 0 to shape[0] - 1:
        Let row be list
        For j from 0 to shape[1] - 1:
            Add 1.0 to row
        Add row to data
    
    Return Algorithms.Matrix with:
        rows as shape[0]
        cols as shape[1]
        data as data

Note: Constant Initialization
Process called "constant_init" that takes shape as List[Integer] and value as Float returns Algorithms.Matrix:
    Let data be list
    For i from 0 to shape[0] - 1:
        Let row be list
        For j from 0 to shape[1] - 1:
            Add value to row
        Add row to data
    
    Return Algorithms.Matrix with:
        rows as shape[0]
        cols as shape[1]
        data as data

Note: Identity Initialization (for square matrices)
Process called "identity_init" that takes size as Integer returns Algorithms.Matrix:
    Let data be list
    For i from 0 to size - 1:
        Let row be list
        For j from 0 to size - 1:
            If i is equal to j:
                Add 1.0 to row
            Otherwise:
                Add 0.0 to row
        Add row to data
    
    Return Algorithms.Matrix with:
        rows as size
        cols as size
        data as data

Note: Orthogonal Initialization
Process called "orthogonal_init" that takes shape as List[Integer] returns Algorithms.Matrix:
    Note: Generate random matrix and compute QR decomposition
    Let random_matrix be random_normal_init with shape as shape and mean as 0.0 and std as 1.0
    Let q_matrix be compute_orthogonal_matrix with matrix as random_matrix
    Return q_matrix

Note: Sparse Initialization
Process called "sparse_init" that takes shape as List[Integer] and sparsity as Float returns Algorithms.Matrix:
    Let data be list
    For i from 0 to shape[0] - 1:
        Let row be list
        For j from 0 to shape[1] - 1:
            If random_uniform with min_val as 0.0 and max_val as 1.0 is greater than sparsity:
                Add random_normal with mean as 0.0 and std as 0.01 to row
            Otherwise:
                Add 0.0 to row
        Add row to data
    
    Return Algorithms.Matrix with:
        rows as shape[0]
        cols as shape[1]
        data as data

Note: Variance Scaling Initialization
Process called "variance_scaling" that takes shape as List[Integer] and scale as Float and mode as String and distribution as String returns Algorithms.Matrix:
    Let fan_in be Float.from with value as shape[0]
    Let fan_out be Float.from with value as shape[1]
    
    Let n be 0.0
    Match mode:
        When "fan_in":
            Set n to fan_in
        When "fan_out":
            Set n to fan_out
        When "fan_avg":
            Set n to (fan_in + fan_out) divided by 2.0
        Otherwise:
            Set n to fan_in
    
    Match distribution:
        When "uniform":
            Let limit be Math.sqrt with x as 3.0 multiplied by scale divided by n
            Return random_uniform_init with shape as shape and min_val as negative limit and max_val as limit
        When "normal":
            Let std be Math.sqrt with x as scale divided by n
            Return random_normal_init with shape as shape and mean as 0.0 and std as std
        Otherwise:
            Return random_normal_init with shape as shape and mean as 0.0 and std as 0.01

Note: Initialize bias vectors
Process called "initialize_bias" that takes size as Integer and init_type as String returns Algorithms.Vector:
    Let data be list
    
    Match init_type:
        When "zeros":
            For i from 0 to size - 1:
                Add 0.0 to data
        When "ones":
            For i from 0 to size - 1:
                Add 1.0 to data
        When "small":
            For i from 0 to size - 1:
                Add 0.01 to data
        Otherwise:
            For i from 0 to size - 1:
                Add 0.0 to data
    
    Return Algorithms.Vector with:
        size as size
        data as data

Note: Initialize embeddings
Process called "initialize_embeddings" that takes vocab_size as Integer and embedding_dim as Integer returns Algorithms.Matrix:
    Note: Initialize embeddings with small random values
    Return random_uniform_init with shape as list containing vocab_size, embedding_dim and min_val as negative 0.1 and max_val as 0.1

Note: Utility functions
Process called "random_uniform" that takes min_val as Float and max_val as Float returns Float:
    Note: Would generate uniform random number in range
    Return Math.random() multiplied by (max_val - min_val) + min_val

Process called "random_normal" that takes mean as Float and std as Float returns Float:
    Note: Would generate normal random number using Box-Muller transform
    Let u1 be Math.random()
    Let u2 be Math.random()
    Let z0 be Math.sqrt with x as negative 2.0 multiplied by Math.log with x as u1 multiplied by Math.cos with x as 2.0 multiplied by Math.pi multiplied by u2
    Return z0 multiplied by std + mean

Process called "compute_orthogonal_matrix" that takes matrix as Algorithms.Matrix returns Algorithms.Matrix:
    Note: Would compute orthogonal matrix via QR decomposition
    Return matrix

Note: Initializer dispatcher
Process called "initialize_weights" that takes shape as List[Integer] and init_type as String returns Algorithms.Matrix:
    Match init_type:
        When "xavier_uniform":
            Return xavier_uniform with shape as shape
        When "xavier_normal":
            Return xavier_normal with shape as shape
        When "he_uniform":
            Return he_uniform with shape as shape
        When "he_normal":
            Return he_normal with shape as shape
        When "lecun_uniform":
            Return lecun_uniform with shape as shape
        When "lecun_normal":
            Return lecun_normal with shape as shape
        When "zeros":
            Return zeros_init with shape as shape
        When "ones":
            Return ones_init with shape as shape
        When "orthogonal":
            Return orthogonal_init with shape as shape
        Otherwise:
            Return xavier_uniform with shape as shape